val result = data.map(x => x * 2).reduce(_ + _)
println(s"Result: $result")
Exit the shell:

:quit
Verification
Check Cluster Status
Verify all processes are running:
jps
Expected output should include:

Master
Worker (multiple instances)
Check Master Web UI:
Navigate to http://localhost:8080
Verify: 2 workers are alive
Check available cores and memory
Check Worker Logs:
ls $SPARK_HOME/logs/
tail -f $SPARK_HOME/logs/spark-*-worker-*.out
Test Cluster Connectivity:
spark-submit --master spark://localhost:7077 \
  --class org.apache.spark.examples.SparkPi \
  $SPARK_HOME/examples/jars/spark-examples*.jar 100
Expected: Pi calculation result displayed

Troubleshooting
Workers not connecting:

Check firewall: sudo ufw status
Verify master URL in worker logs
Ensure ports 7077, 8080, 8081 are available
Out of Memory errors:

Reduce SPARK_WORKER_MEMORY in spark-env.sh
Decrease spark.executor.memory in application
Port conflicts:

netstat -tulpn | grep -E '7077|8080|8081'
Cleanup
Stop the cluster:

$SPARK_HOME/sbin/stop-worker.sh
$SPARK_HOME/sbin/stop-master.sh
Verify all processes stopped:

jps
Conclusion
You have successfully:

Installed Apache Spark in distributed mode
Configured a master-worker cluster architecture
Started and managed Spark cluster services
Submitted and executed distributed applications
Monitored cluster performance through Web UI
This setup simulates a production Spark cluster on a single machine, providing hands-on experience with distributed computing concepts. In production environments, master and workers run on separate physical machines, but the configuration principles remain the same.

Key Takeaways:

Spark's master-worker architecture enables distributed processing
Configuration files control cluster behavior and resource allocation
The Web UI provides real-time monitoring and debugging capabilities
Applications can be submitted in multiple languages (Python, Scala, Java)
